Use this method (and the corresponding

method) to complete your app’s initialization and make any final tweaks. This method is called after state restoration has occurred but before your app’s window and other UI have been presented. At some point after this method returns, the system calls another of your app delegate’s methods to move the app to the active (foreground) state or the background state.
This method represents your last chance to process any keys in the
dictionary. If you did not evaluate the keys in your
method, you should look at them in this method and provide an appropriate response.
Objects that are not the app delegate can access the same
dictionary values by observing the notification named
and accessing the notification’s
dictionary. That notification is sent shortly after this method returns.
For app initialization, it is highly recommended that you use this method and the
method and do not use the
method, which is intended only for apps that run on older versions of iOS.
The return result from this method is combined with the return result from the
method to determine if a URL should be handled. If either method returns
, the URL is not handled. If you do not implement one of the methods, only the return value of the implemented method is considered.
